<DOC><DOCNO> AP890810-0127 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1737EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Hostages-Glance     08-10 0312</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostages-Glance,0338</SECOND><HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0670 to fix cycle designator</HEAD><HEAD>Developments in the Hostage Crisis</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here are the latest developments in the hostage crisis:</TEXT><NOTE>LEBANON</NOTE><TEXT>   Israel's militia allies in south Lebanon attacked two U.N.peacekeepers who tried to stop a roundup of Shiite Moslems after anIsraeli convoy was bombed, according to U.N reports.   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the peacekeepers, said the twoNorwegian soldiers were injured by flying stones Wednesday whenmilitiamen were refused passage at a checkpoint and fired at theirlegs.   Hezbollah, the pro-Iranian group believed to sponsorhostage-holders, took responsibility for the suicide truck bombingWednesday, which wounded five Israeli soldiers and a member of theallied South Lebanon Army militia.</TEXT><NOTE>IRAN</NOTE><TEXT>   An Iranian newspaper said indirect talks between Iran and theUnited States would begin within days.   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted theEnglish-language Tehran Times, which is close to President HashemiRafsanjani, as saying talks would be conducted through a thirdcountry, probably Pakistan.   Later Thursday, however, the agency issued a dispatch sayingreports of talks with the United States were ``suspicious'' andquoted sources as saying none were being held.</TEXT><NOTE>ISRAEL</NOTE><TEXT>   An aide to Yitzhak Shamir said President Bush and the Israeliprime minister had agreed to coordinate efforts to free the 16Western hostages in Lebanon, who include eight Americans, andIsraeli prisoners.   Avi Pazner said the decision was reached in a 10-minutetelephone call Wednesday from Shamir to Bush.</TEXT><NOTE>UNITED STATES</NOTE><TEXT>   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said of the Shamir-Bushconversation: ``We've generally tried to be forthcoming with whatwe are doing, and they have been forthcoming wth what they'redoing. However, I would not characterize it as coordination.''   He said it was ``premature'' to expect direct talks with Iranand ``we're nowhere near that,'' but indicated indirect contactswould continue.</TEXT></DOC>